     UK           micros.hensa.ac.uk       148.88.8.84     pub/aminet/   8500
   All these mirrors have a directory @{b}/pub/aminet@{ub}, where you will find much
stuff. Please use a mirror close to you! Some other important hosts are
     ftp.funet.fi             (Finland)
     ftp.isca.uiowa.edu       (USA)
     ftp.hawaii.edu           (USA)
     ftp.cso.uiuc.edu         (USA)
     ftp.dfv.rwth-aachen.de   (Germany)
   Note that grind, aachen and erlangen have the full collection of Fish
disks available! See @{"Fish disk xxx" Link "Fish disk xxx"}.  If you don't find a specific file on
your local mirror, try @{b}ftp.wustl.edu@{ub}, @{b}ftp.uni-paderborn.de@{ub} or
@{b}ftp.doc.ic.ac.uk@{ub}; they keep all files.

   To connect to a special host (ftp.uni-erlangen.de for example), you
should type
     ftp ftp.uni-erlangen.de

The host answers by requesting your login. You should type
     ftp

No you are asked for a password. Please type your Email address here, if
you have one. If not, use the password ftp.

   Now you're inside the host. There is a number of commands you may execute
here. The most important are:
@{i}?@{ui}
     Prints the help text of the FTP command. Additionally you may type @{i}?
     command@{ui} to get information on a special command.

@{i}bin@{ui}
     Tells the FTP program that you whish to transfer binary files. It is
     always a good choice to type bin as the very first command! Files you
     load without the bin command can be corrupt.

@{i}get <file>@{ui}
     Loads the given file from the host. On most Unix machines you can type
     something like @{b}get file.txt -@{ub} or @{b}get file.txt |more@{ub} to show a text on
     the screen. Note that there @{i}must not@{ui} be any blank between the | and
     the word more!

@{i}mget <pat>@{ui}
     Loads the given files. pat may contain Unix style like wildcards.

@{i}put <file>@{ui}
@{i}mput <pat>@{ui}
     Like get and mget, but transfer files from you to the remote host. This
     is in most cases not allowed, except for a special directory called
     @{b}incoming@{ub}. You can place files here which you want to make public.

@{i}cd <dir>@{ui}
     Like the usual cd command. The commands get, mget, put, mput, dir and
     ls refer to the current working directory.

@{i}dir [<dir>]@{ui}
@{i}ls [<dir>]@{ui}
     Like @{b}list@{ub} and @{b}dir@{ub} on the Amiga. Note that the FTP-dir corresponds to
     the Amiga-list!

@{i}bye@{ui}
     Leaves the FTP program.

   When you have used FTP for the first times you will notice, that you
always begin with executing the same steps:
  1. Type the login (ftp in most cases)

  2. Type the password (your mail address in most cases)

  3. Enter the bin command

  4. Change the current working directory (@{b}/pub/aminet@{ub} for example)
        This may get executed automatically. What you need is a file called
@{b}.netrc@{ub} in your home directory. Note that it needs to be protected against
others! The FTP program doesn't use it, if it can be read by anything else
than you. (Protection is set using the command @{b}chmod go-rwx .netrc@{ub}.) The
.netrc file contains some entries for your most favourite FTP sites, each
separated by empy lines. A typicel entry may look like this:
     machine ftp.uni-erlangen.de
     login ftp
     password <your mail address> or <ftp>
     macdef init
         bin
         cd pub/aminet
   Note that on some machines it is possible to use the machine name
@{b}default@{ub} which meets all machines not listed in .netrc.


@EndNode

